<font color="#FF0000">CHANGE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug 14  6:19:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook, that was a great post. Thanks, for sharing the poem and the feelings of the guys at the memorial service.  This too, is healing.  The feelings that you and others experienced pull all of us up and out of the mud.<br>
I agree with Tom's statements.  Leave those things that we can't change alone.  You and I and all of us here will not or cannot ever change anyone's belief systems about what was wrong or right. It is a waste of time and energy.<br>
Kind of like the old saying about trying to teach a pig to dance.  It pisses off the pig and makes you look dumb.<br>
We will (as Vets) meet people until the day we die whose views and standards about the Vietnam War will piss us off.  How we deal with that depends on how much time and energy we are willing to devote to change.<br>
I for one, can look at differing views. Not change them and maybe not understand them but accept them as different. If they piss me off, I will state that they piss me off.  But I learned the hard way that all we can do is attempt to put our views on the table as well.  This is part of healing.  Putting &quot;grays&quot; into our lives.  Every thing is not &quot;black and white&quot;. People in our squad will no longer be put in harm's way if we say &quot;I don't know&quot;.  People will no longer be wounded or maimed if we say &quot;You have a valid point but I disagree.&quot;<br>
We can't change the past. <br>
Semper Fi, Marine!<br>

